    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1943-10-04T13:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1943-10-04T13:00:00-05:00" n="1"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d1">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">821.00/1549: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Colombia</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Lane</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Bogotá</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1943-10-04T13:00:00-05:00"
                            >October 4, 1943—1 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received 5:35 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>1779. From an independent conservative source friendly to the Government, I am
                    informed that it is being recommended to the President<note n="1" xml:id="d1fn1"
                        >Alfonso López.</note> that he declare war against the Axis Powers, giving
                    as a specific reason the action of Germany in holding the Pope as prisoner. This
                    source stated that the Conservative Party would applaud the Government’s action
                    especially as the Liberal Party has in the past not been associated with a
                    pro-Roman Catholic attitude. It is felt that such a move would not only divert
                    public opinion …but would serve to unite the country.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Lane</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
